To factor in the transfer of electronic charge, we distributed our studied compounds into three segments such as donor, π-spacer, and acceptor. TDM pictographs illustrate a reasonable proportion of diagonal electronic charge transference (CT) in all the designed chromophores. From comparative study of TDM heat maps of all the compounds (DOCR1 and DOCD2-DOCD6) it is observed that they exhibit almost similar behavior. TDM pictographs in S0–S1 energy level (Fig. 7) confirm that electrons are significantly shifted from π-spacer to the acceptor counterparts which accelerate the transfer of electrons without any restriction. The results of TDM heat maps suggest schematic separation in the excited transition state that is significant for the production of NLO materials. The difference between electrical and optical band gap energies is called binding energy, which is a major tool to determine the optoelectronic characteristics of the designed compounds. Equation (5) is employed to estimate the binding energy of the reference and designed chromophores67.5Eb=EL-H-Eopt\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
